Modeling Pulse Rate Using Demographic and Dietary Information

Patrick Wu

2020-12-10

1 Setup and Data Ingest

This study uses data from the 2017-2018 National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey to model pulse rate using various demographic and dietary characteristics.

1.1 R Setup

These code chunks specify options in R and load the necessary libraries.

1.2 Data Ingest

First, the data must be pulled from the NHANES website. NHANES data are publicly available, and the data files are saved locally for easier access. The variables to be used in the analysis are selected from the data sets.

#Pulling data from NHANES

#bp_raw <- nhanes('BPX_J') %>% tibble()

#saveRDS(bp_raw, "data/BPX_J.Rds")

#demo_raw <- nhanes('DEMO_J') %>% tibble()

#saveRDS(demo_raw, "data/DEMO_J.Rds")

#day1_raw <- nhanes('DR1TOT_J') %>% tibble()

#saveRDS(day1_raw, "data/DR1TOT_J.Rds")

#Data can now be read from saved RDS files

bp_raw <- readRDS("data/BPX_J.Rds")

demo_raw <- readRDS("data/DEMO_J.Rds")

day1_raw <- readRDS("data/DR1TOT_J.Rds")

#Selecting variables

demo <- demo_raw %>% select(SEQN, RIDSTATR, RIAGENDR, RIDRETH3, RIDAGEYR)

day1 <- day1_raw %>% select(SEQN, DR1TSODI, DR1TKCAL, DBQ095Z)

bp <- bp_raw %>% select(SEQN, BPXPLS)

Only dietary data from Day 1 is used as it is more complete. Therefore, some information is lost in the interest of applying a consistent analytical procedure to all subjects while maximizing sample size.

2 Merging the Data

The next step is to merge the data pulled from different NHANES files. The data files can be merged using the ID variable SEQN.

#Merging datasets

temp1 <- left_join(demo, bp, by = "SEQN")

nhanesdata <- left_join(temp1, day1, by = "SEQN")

No difficulties were experienced in merging the data, and the data will be checked in more detail later on.

3 Cleaning the Data

The data documentation contains detailed information about the variables in the NHANES data set. Missing values will be removed for this analysis. In addition, one variable (DBQ095Z, the type of table salt used) contains a Dont Know value that will also be treated as missing. Categorical variables are also made factors and the levels are renamed to reflect the identities of the categories. Finally, only subjects who participated in both the interview and examination portions of the survey are included, and empty levels and labels are removed.

#Evaluating missingness and cleaning data

nhanesdata <- nhanesdata %>% mutate(DBQ095Z = na_if(DBQ095Z, "99"),
                                      sex = fct_recode(factor(RIAGENDR),
                                "Male" = "1",
                                "Female" = "2"),
                                RIDRETH3 = fct_recode(factor(RIDRETH3),

                                                      "Non-Hispanic White" = "3",

                                                      "Non-Hispanic Asian" = "6",
                                                      "Other Race" = "7"),

                                DBQ095Z = fct_recode(factor(DBQ095Z),
                                                     "Ordinary salt" = "1",
                                                     "Lite salt" = "2",
                                                     "Salt substitute" = "3",

  filter(RIDSTATR == 2) %>% subset(select = -RIAGENDR)

4 My Research Question

The National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey is carried out on subjects selected using a stratified method from the US population. First, counties are divided into groups based on their characteristics and sampled randomly. Then, the counties are subdivided and these subdivisions are sampled. Then, a sample of households is selected from each selected subdivision and people from those households are randomly selected. The survey contains both an interview and a physical examination component only subjects who participated in both are included in this study. The research question for this study is as follows:

How effectively can sodium intake be used to predict pulse rate, and how much is this prediction improved when considering other demographic and dietary characteristics including sex, race, age, caloric intake, and type of table salt used?

My expectation is that increasing sodium intake will be associated with increasing pulse rate, and that the use of additional predictors will improve the model significantly.

5 My Final Variables

5.1 Codebook

The subjects of this study are 6086 2017-2018 NHANES participants aged 8 to at least 80 with complete data on the variables listed below.

Variable Name Type Description Original Name
SEQN - Subject identifying code -
RIDSTATR - Code 2 = Both interviewed and examined -
RIDRETH3 6-cat Predictor; Race/ethnicity (Mexican American, Other Hispanic, Non-Hispanic White, Non-Hispanic Black, Non-Hispanic Asian, or Other Race) -
RIDAGEYR Quant Predictor; Age in years (Values of 80 and over coded as 80) -
BPXPLS Quant Outcome; Pulse rate in beats per minute (30s pulse * 2) -
DR1TSODI Quant Key predictor; Total sodium intake for one day in mg calculated using USDA Food and Nutrient Database for Dietary Studies -
DR1TKCAL Quant Predictor; Total caloric intake for one day in kcal calculated using USDA Food and Nutrient Database for Dietary Studies -
DBQ095Z 4-cat Predictor; Type of table salt used (Ordinary, lite, salt substitute, or doesnt use) -
sex Binary Predictor; Sex (Male or female) RIAGENDR

  • There is no missing data for any variable. Subjects with missing data were dropped from the data set on the assumption that data were missing completely at random.

  • Ranges for all quantitative variables were checked. There are some extreme values for sodium and calorie intake. However, after consideration, I believe these values are plausible and will not modify or exclude them.

  • All categorical variables have 2-6 levels, and are included as factors. All levels have at least 64 subjects.

  • All subjects were included in both the questionnaire and examination. Subjects range in age from 8 to at least 80.

6 Partitioning the Data

The next step is to partition the data into a training sample, containing about 80% of the data, and a test sample, containing the other 20% of the data.

set.seed(12252020)

nhanes_train <- nhanes_comp %>%
  slice_sample(., prop = 0.80)
nhanes_test <- anti_join(nhanes_comp, nhanes_train, by = "SEQN")

dim(nhanes_train)
[1] 4868    9
dim(nhanes_test)
[1] 1218    9

The training sample will be used to build the models. Performance in both the training sample and the test sample will be used to evaluate the models.

7 Transforming the Outcome

The next step is to examine the distributions of the variables and consider transformations. The first variable to consider is the outcome, pulse rate.

The distribution of pulse rate is noticeably right-skewed.

mod_box <- lm(BPXPLS ~ DR1TSODI, data = nhanes_train)

mod_box2 <- lm(BPXPLS ~ DR1TSODI + RIDRETH3 + RIDAGEYR + DR1TKCAL + DBQ095Z + sex, data = nhanes_train)

boxCox(mod_box)

boxCox(mod_box2)

The Box-Cox plots suggest a log transformation.

ggplot(nhanes_train, aes(x = log(BPXPLS))) +

The distribution for the outcome after applying a log transformation looks much better. This transformation will be used in fitting the models.

The big model has an R-squared value of 0.115, which is disappointing considering the number of variables used. This is reflected in the adjusted R-squared value being lower than the multiple R-squared value. Age and sex were the variables with the most significant P-values.

The intercept of the model is 4.38 with a 90% confidence interval of 4.36 to 4.39. This corresponds to the expected value for the log of the pulse rate of a person who is non-Hispanic White, non-female, uses ordinary table salt, and has no sodium or caloric intake and an age of zero.

The coefficient for age is -0.0023 with a 90% confidence interval of -0.0025 to -0.0021. This value corresponds to the change in log of pulse rate expected with an increase in age of 1 year, assuming all other variables are held constant. The confidence interval indicates that increasing age is associated with a decrease in pulse rate at the 10% significance level when accounting for the other factors in the model.

The coefficient for Mexican American is -0.0144 with a 90% confidence interval of -0.0260 to -0.0028. This value corresponds to the difference in log of pulse rate expected between Mexican Americans and non-Hispanic Whites if all other variables are the same. The confidence interval indicates that the mean pulse rate for Mexican Americans is lower than that of non-Hispanic whites at a 10% significance level when accounting for the other factors in the model.

The coefficient for Other Hispanic is -0.0134 with a 90% confidence interval of -0.0272 to 0.0004. This value corresponds to the difference in log of pulse rate expected between people in the Other Hispanic category and the non-Hispanic White category if all other variables are the same. The confidence interval indicates that the mean pulse rate for other Hispanics is not detectably different from that of non-Hispanic Whites at a 10% significance level when accounting for the other factors in the model.

The coefficient for Non-Hispanic Black is -0.0231 with a 90% confidence interval of -0.0330 to -0.0132. This value corresponds to the difference in log of pulse rate expected between people in the Non-Hispanic Black category and the Non-Hispanic White category if all other variables values are the same. The confidence interval indicates that the mean pulse rate for non-Hispanic Black participants is lower than that of non-Hispanic White participants at a 10% significance level when accounting for the other factors in the model.

11 Model Validation

11.1 Calculating Prediction Errors

In this section, both models are applied to the test sample and the predictions are transformed back into pulse rate values so that residuals can be calculated.

aug_big <- augment(mbig, newdata = nhanes_test) %>% 
  mutate(mod_name = "big",
         BPXPLS_fit = exp(.fitted),
         BPXPLS_res = BPXPLS - BPXPLS_fit) %>%
  select(SEQN, mod_name, BPXPLS, BPXPLS_fit, BPXPLS_res, everything())

aug_small <- augment(msmall, newdata = nhanes_test) %>% 
  mutate(mod_name = "small",
         BPXPLS_fit = exp(.fitted),
         BPXPLS_res = BPXPLS - BPXPLS_fit) %>%
  select(SEQN, mod_name, BPXPLS, BPXPLS_fit, BPXPLS_res, everything())

test_comp <- union(aug_big, aug_small) %>%
  arrange(SEQN, mod_name)

The predictions of the two models look similar overall. However, the predictions for the small model seem to be somewhat more clustered together, with a smaller range of predicted values. 12 Discussion

12.1 Chosen Model

Based on performance in both the training and test sample, I choose the big model. The big model performed better on more quantitative measures, including adjusted R-squared and AIC in the training sample, as well as MAPE and RMSPE in the test sample. The primary disadvantage of the big model is collinearity, but the generalized variance inflation factor is not high enough to present a major issue.

12.2 Answering My Question

Sodium intake was not effective in predicting pulse rate; the association between these variables was extremely slight. Of the additional characteristics considered, age and sex were most effective in predicting pulse rate, but even these were not enough to produce an interesting or effective model overall. Only about 11% of the variance in pulse rate was accounted for by the full list of predictors used in this study. Also of note is the fact that the relationship between sodium intake and pulse rate was the opposite of what was expected, with increasing sodium intake associated with decreasing pulse rate. However, the effect size of this relationship is extremely small and not practically meaningful.

12.3 Next Steps

The current set of predictors is insufficient to develop an interesting or useful model of pulse rate. Therefore, the next step would be to consider additional predictors that might exhibit a stronger relationship with pulse rate. For example, measures related to physical fitness, such as BMI and amount of regular exercise, could be considered in order to develop a more effective model.

12.4 Reflection

The biggest thing I would have changed in this study knowing what I know now would be to pick different variables that might yield more interesting results. However, despite not developing an effective model the results of this study were interesting in their own way. In addition, despite already being aware of this issue, I found the data cleaning and management and the writing portion of the assignment to be more time-consuming relative to the analysis than I expected.
